Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions:¶

  • How many different segments of customers are there?
  • How are these segments different from each other?
  • What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description:¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call.

  • Customer key - Identifier for the customer
  • Average Credit Limit - Average credit limit across all the credit cards
  • Total credit cards - Total number of credit cards
  • Total visits bank - Total number of bank visits
  • Total visits online - total number of online visits
  • Total calls made - Total number of calls made by the customer

2. Insights from EDA¶

Estimation on Number of clusters from EDA¶

  • From Avg_Credit_limit, we can see minimum of 3 groups from histogram kde where there are one huge peaks, a slight projection as two groups and outliers as another group.

    - Even the data where Avg_Credit_limit<50000,50000>Avg_Credit_limit<75000,Avg_Credit_limit>75000 show different 
  behaviours with respect to Total_visits_online,Total_calls_made etc

  • Total_Credit_Cards kde shows 2 peaks so minimun of 2 clusters with respect to Total_Credit_Cards.

Insights from Histplots

  • Avg_Credit_Limit distribution is left skewed.
  • Majority of customers - the Avg credit limit is <25000
  • Maximum customers had 2 bank visits.
  • There are approx equal number of customers for (0,1,3,4,5) bank visits.
  • Majority of customers has less than or equal to 2 online visits.
  • Very few customers have more than 8 online visits.
  • There is huge fall in number of customers who made more than 4 calls.

  • Majority of customers made less than or equal to 4 calls.

    Conclusions from Histplots

    • Looks like many of the customers have Avg_credit_limit<25000
    • As there are more number of customers with 2 bank visits, it looks like it requires minimum of 2 bank visits to get most of the services from bank
    • As there are more number of customers have done only 0-2 online vists,it looks like major customer base is not confortable with online visits.
    • As There is huge fall in number of customers who made more than 4 calls, we can derive that most of complaints are getting solved within 4 calls.

Insights from Boxplots

  • There are outliers towards right in Avg_Credit_limit boxplot.
  • 75 percent of customers have credit limit <50000

clusters=range(2,10)  # setting a range of clusters to implement KMeans algorithm 

meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k,random_state=0)  # define KMeans function for each k vlaues
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)                # fit the function for each k value
    prediction = model.predict(subset_scaled_df) # predict the cluster index for each sample
    distortion = sum(np.min(cdist(subset_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / subset_scaled_df.shape[0] # Calculate the distorsions for each k 
                           
    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print('Number of Clusters:', k, '\tAverage Distortion:', distortion)

4.Hierarchial Clustering¶

Chophenet Correlation Coefficient¶

Calculate cophenet index for different cluster derived using differnt linkage methods and distances.

  • cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
  • closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
In [56]:
# calculate cophenet index for specified distance metrics and linkage methods.

dist_metrics = [ 'euclidean','chebyshev','mahalanobis','cityblock']   # create distance metrics  list
link_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted']          # create link methods list
hc_coph_list1 = []       # create empty list to capture list of tuples as ( distance, linkage, c )
high_coph_corr1 = 0      # variable to capture the highest c value. initialzed the variable with 0.
high_dm_lm1 = ['','']   # list to capture distance metric and linkage method that gives highest c value

for dm in dist_metrics:     #iterate on list dist_metrics
    for lm in link_methods: #iterate on list link_methods
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)   # call linkage method to generate linkage matrix
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df)) # calculate cophenet coefficient
        hc_coph_list1.append((dm,lm,c))                       # append the tuple of dm,lm,c to list
        if high_coph_corr1 < c:                               # get the highest c value in the entire iteration cycle
            high_coph_corr1 = c
            high_dm_lm1[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm1[1] = lm

#create a pandas dataframe with all Cophenet_corr_coeff and corresponding distance-linkage pair
df = pd.DataFrame({'temp':hc_coph_list1})  
hc_coph_pdf1 = pd.DataFrame(df['temp'].tolist(),index=df.index,columns=['distance','linkage','Cophenet_corr'])
hc_coph_pdf1.head(30)        # display the calculated Cophenet_corr as dataframe

for lm in link_methods:    #iterate on list link_methods

Dendrogram Graphs¶

In [61]:
# List of all linkage methods and distance types to check

dist_metrics = [ 'euclidean','chebyshev','mahalanobis','cityblock']
link_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted']

# Create a subplot image
graphs =  len(link_methods)*len(dist_metrics)
fig, axs = plt.subplots(graphs, 1, figsize=(25, 125))

i=0
# Enumerate through the list of all methods above
# Get linkage, plot dendrogram, calculate cophenetic coefficient
for dm in range(len(dist_metrics)):
    for lm in range(len(link_methods)):
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dist_metrics[dm], method=link_methods[lm]) # call linkage method to generate linkage matrix
        dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i]);  # draw dendrogram
        # set title
        axs[i].set_title(f'Dendrogram ({link_methods[lm].capitalize()} Linkage,{dist_metrics[dm].capitalize()} Distance)',fontweight="bold", size=20)
        # calculate coph_corr
        coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        axs[i].annotate(f'Cophenetic\nCoefficient\n{coph_corr:0.2f}', 
                    (0.80, 0.80),
                    xycoords='axes fraction', size=20)
        i=i+1

  • As per chophenet coefficient, (euclidean average 0.920659) this pair gives highest chophenet value but (euclidean,average) dendrogram is not clear, lot of overlaps and only two cluster distinctions.

  • As per Dendrograms,Ward Linkage and Euclidean distance dendrogram shows clear separate and distinct clusters. its chophenet coefficient score(0.82) is also decently high not very less. also it shows number of clusters as 4 which coincides with KMeans selected algorithm from elbow method.

    • so I select the pair (Ward Linkage and Euclidean distance and n_clusters=4) for Hierarchial clustering as final algorithm to do clustering on data.

  • I also prefer to select citiblock and average pair (with n_clusters=3) for analysis as this pair has high cophenet coefficient after euclidena distance pairs

5.Average Silhouette scores¶

  • Compute the mean Silhouette Coefficient of all samples.

  • The Silhouette Coefficient is calculated using the mean intra-cluster distance (a) and the mean nearest-cluster distance (b) for each sample.

  • The best value is 1 and the worst value is -1. Values near 0 indicate overlapping clusters. Negative values generally indicate that a sample has been assigned to the wrong cluster, as a different cluster is more similar.

Calculate Silhouette scores for KMeans Algorithsm k=(2-9)

In [71]:
sil_score = []  # declare a list
cluster_list = list(range(2,10))   # range of k values to calculate
for n_clusters in cluster_list:    # iterate on cluster_list
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters,random_state=0) #  Implement KMeans algorithm
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((subset_scaled_df))
    score = silhouette_score(subset_scaled_df, preds)  # calculate silhouette_score
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {})".format(n_clusters, score))

    
#Draw graph with k on x axis and silhouette score on y axis

plt.ylabel('silhouette_score')

HCsil_score ={}   # declare a dictionary to capture final socres

dist_metrics = ['euclidean','chebyshev','cityblock']
link_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average','ward']
for dm in range(len(dist_metrics)):
    for lm in range(len(link_methods)):
        HCcluster_pair=()
        if(link_methods[lm] == 'ward'):
            HCmodel = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4,affinity='euclidean', linkage=link_methods[lm]) #AgglomerativeClustering Implementation for ward whch required only euclidean distance
            HCcluster_pair = ('euclidean',link_methods[lm])
        else:
            HCmodel = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4,affinity=dist_metrics[dm], linkage=link_methods[lm]) #AgglomerativeClustering Implementation for all other linkages
            HCcluster_pair = (dist_metrics[dm],link_methods[lm])
        HCpreds = HCmodel.fit_predict(subset_scaled_df)
        HCscore = silhouette_score(subset_scaled_df, HCpreds)
        HCsil_score[HCcluster_pair] = HCscore

8. Key Questions¶

How many different segments of customers are there?¶

Based on KMeans, the overall customers can be divided into following groups.

- i) low credit limit group [low income group] 
- ii) mid credit limit group [ mid income group]
- iii) mixed credit limit group [ mixed income group]
- iv) high credit limit group [ high income group ]

if you want to condense the groups : ii) and iii) can be merged to gether. this is shown in Heirarchial Clustering[( Manhattan/Citiblock, Average ) pair, n_clusters = 3 ] algorithm.

How are these segments different from each other¶

  • for ii) and iii) groups most of the boxplots fall in same range. only difference between mid-income group and mixed income group is mid-income group have made extremely high bank visits. which implied that they might have mobile occupations like representatives, journalists etc.

  • Other two groups (i and iv) are low credit limit and high credit limit groups respectively.

  • The only group which has made more online visits is high income group.The others have made comparitively very less online visits.

  • The low income group have made more calls . we may conclude that they have many complaints or may need one - one asistance to get services.

  • The mid income group have made extremely high bank visits.

  • The high income group have made more online visits indicating that they are comfortable with online services.

  • The high income group have made less call indicating that they did not have more complaints.

Business Recommendations¶

Overall Business Recommendations

Marketing team to run personalised campaigns

  • We see few outliers in Avg_Credit_Limit of Low income group class. May be we can do further look on customer profiles and increse credit limit for few customers to increase the business.

  • One cluster with mid credit limit showed high bank visits . which implies that they may be on travel most of the times so that they are able to visit bank often. so we can offer them some special offers or discounts on targeted purchases by doing further analysis on their spending patterns.

  • Bank can design trageted offers based on clusters properties to increase their Avg_credit_Limit ,Total_Credit_Cards

  • The bank offers can be communicated to customers based on their comfortable medium. Example:Few consumers have made more calls. they are more comfortable with one to one assistance. so Bank can reach these customers regarding the offers on phone.

  • In Mixed Income group category, As there are wide range of customers with varied Avg_Credit_limit and Number_credit_cards, Marketing team can design generic offers or schemes to this segment.

  • Marketing team can try to retain High Credit Limit customers by giving similar kind of offers as they show good customer satisfaction parameters.

  • Customers who did less bank visits and less online visits can be reached through mails or calls to communicate the bank offers or schemas.

  • Few customers who have more number of credit cards. they might look for some offers to increase their credit limit. so Bank can work on such schems.

Service Delivery team to upgrade service delivery model

  • Majority of customers have done very few online visits. Only group which made more online visits is high income group. This implies that the website or online services may be more complex to understand for normal population.need some improvement to make it easy to use.

  • Group with low credit limit have made very high number of calls. This implies that this group is not satisfied with the services or might have more queries. As this is the majority group, The company needs to address their concerns to prevent losing existing customers.

  • There is huge fall in number of customers who made more than 4 calls, we can derive that most of complaints are getting solved within 4 calls.This number(4 calls) can be reduced to improve customer satisfaction rate.

  • High income group had made only 0-1 bank visits. meaning all services are available on online. only issue the online services are not understandable to all customer class.

  • Service delivery processes are complex to understand for self use. so customers are making more calls to clarify on queries. Service delivery team can work on simplifying service delivery workflows.

  • Service delivery team can continue their interaction with High Credit Limit customers in same way with this team as they show good customer satisfaction parameters.

  • The EDA shows that maximum number of customers made minimum of 2-3 bank visits. Team can work on how to remove the dependency of mandatory bank visits on service delivery.
  • Service delivery team can validate on phone calls like what are major services or clarifications asked on phone calls. and can work on those issues so that the customers does not call on same issues again. so we can reduce number of calls by doing so.
  • Service delivery team can reach customers through mails for customers who made less bank and online visits to provide their services.
